the interface layer is the semiotic layer within the system

25:50.000 --> 25:57.000
that allows for the translation between users that are participating

25:57.000 --> 26:00.000
in the larger system and that system itself.

26:00.000 --> 26:04.000
So in the simplest sense you're using your computer,

26:04.000 --> 26:07.000
you're seeing all the buttons with words on them on the screen.

26:07.000 --> 26:11.000
Of all of the possible things you could do with your computer,

26:11.000 --> 26:13.000
of all the possible things your computer could do

26:13.000 --> 26:15.000
now that it's connected to the internet,

26:15.000 --> 26:19.000
all of those trillions and trillions and trillions of possibilities

26:19.000 --> 26:25.000
are reduced to a composable array of several dozen menu items

26:25.000 --> 26:29.000
that you can sort of choose between.

26:29.000 --> 26:33.000
That map reduction of all of those possibilities

26:33.000 --> 26:36.000
into this composable array of menu functions

26:36.000 --> 26:42.000
is unavoidably ideological, is unavoidably political

26:42.000 --> 26:44.000
if you want to think of it in those terms,

26:44.000 --> 26:48.000
constriction or collapse of the space of possibilities

26:48.000 --> 26:51.000
into a range of options.

26:51.000 --> 26:53.000
I would also argue though in a certain sense

26:53.000 --> 26:56.000
that this is to a certain sense unavoidable as well

26:56.000 --> 26:59.000
in that it has, when I call it a map reduction,

26:59.000 --> 27:01.000
this is exactly what it is.

27:01.000 --> 27:04.000
In the same way in which you don't want a map of your city

27:04.000 --> 27:07.000
that is one-to-one with your city,

27:07.000 --> 27:08.000
you don't want a map of the city

27:08.000 --> 27:11.000
that includes absolutely everything in your city on it

27:11.000 --> 27:16.000
and would be in essence the most accurate map possible of your city.

27:16.000 --> 27:18.000
You want a map that only includes,

27:18.000 --> 27:22.000
that gets rid of 99% of everything that's there,

27:22.000 --> 27:26.000
that only shows you that 1% that might be the most relevant

27:26.000 --> 27:31.000
for the purposes of the abstractions of navigation.

27:31.000 --> 27:33.000
Interface layer functions in a similar way.

27:33.000 --> 27:37.000
It's a kind of reductive abstraction of the space

27:37.000 --> 27:40.000
of the vectors of navigation through the space.

27:40.000 --> 27:43.000
And because of this function of simplification,

27:43.000 --> 27:50.000
it also allows for the network effects of the millions of people

27:50.000 --> 27:56.000
for whom this map is legible to actually use the system,

27:56.000 --> 28:00.000
to participate in the system, to generate value for the system,

28:00.000 --> 28:03.000
to have value generated for them from the system

28:03.000 --> 28:07.000
because of its simplification and its arrangement

28:07.000 --> 28:09.000
in the same way in which a simple map

28:09.000 --> 28:13.000
makes the city navigable for more people.

28:13.000 --> 28:18.000
On the one hand, you can see this as having a kind of democratizing effect,

28:18.000 --> 28:22.000
but there's a political valence of that.

28:22.000 --> 28:25.000
There's a political valence in the map reduction problem itself

28:25.000 --> 28:27.000
and the ideological constraint.

28:27.000 --> 28:29.000
There's also a political function of this

28:29.000 --> 28:32.000
in that in the network's effects of participation,

28:32.000 --> 28:41.000
you have the kinds of aggregations of user participants in such a way

28:41.000 --> 28:44.000
that they themselves enter into social relations

28:44.000 --> 28:48.000
that they wouldn't have been able to do so otherwise.

28:48.000 --> 28:51.000
So we're still kind of setting the groundwork, I think,

