31:54.000 --> 31:57.000
If the stack was a book that was about

31:57.000 --> 32:01.000
what is planetary scale computation and how does it work,

32:01.000 --> 32:05.000
the next book is really more trying to speak to this question again.

32:05.000 --> 32:07.000
What is planetary scale computation for?

32:07.000 --> 32:11.000
How do we would see it in longer historical terms

32:11.000 --> 32:14.000
and maybe even in geologic terms,

32:14.000 --> 32:17.000
in sort of anthropocene scale kinds of terms.

32:17.000 --> 32:23.000
What does it mean now that it's possible for human societies

32:23.000 --> 32:27.000
and indeed human societies to calculate their own,

32:27.000 --> 32:29.000
to model and calculate their own processes

32:29.000 --> 32:31.000
with such speed and clarity,

32:31.000 --> 32:34.000
but also in many ways how it's possible for,

32:34.000 --> 32:36.000
if you think of the entire apparatus itself,

32:36.000 --> 32:40.000
of the satellite systems, the transoceanic cables,

32:40.000 --> 32:43.000
the data centers, this entire planet,

32:43.000 --> 32:46.000
this entire kind of artificial crust

32:46.000 --> 32:49.000
that we have produced around the surface of the planet,

32:49.000 --> 32:51.000
what it means for also to create for a planet

32:51.000 --> 32:56.000
to be able to model itself and act back upon itself

32:56.000 --> 33:02.000
with such sophistication.

33:02.000 --> 33:05.000
How do we understand this even in geological terms

33:05.000 --> 33:07.000
in terms of the arc and history of the planet?

33:07.000 --> 33:10.000
And so there's some questioning then

33:10.000 --> 33:14.000
of how to locate the question of planetary scale computation

33:14.000 --> 33:16.000
within some of the philosophical questionings

33:16.000 --> 33:21.000
after planetarity itself and how this would function.

33:21.000 --> 33:23.000
Now, to the question of the capitalist pricing problem,

33:23.000 --> 33:26.000
back to this, the capitalist pricing problem,

33:26.000 --> 33:29.000
as I define it, and again, it's rather schematic,

33:29.000 --> 33:31.000
has to do with the negative externalities

33:31.000 --> 33:34.000
within economic transactions

33:34.000 --> 33:38.000
and this trying to locate the question of economics,

33:38.000 --> 33:44.000
the ontology of economics within that of ecology more broadly.

33:44.000 --> 33:46.000
Excuse me.

33:46.000 --> 33:49.000
So the question of the ontology of economics,

33:49.000 --> 33:52.000
that is, what is value? What is valuable?

33:52.000 --> 33:56.000
And how can something be identified as valuable

33:56.000 --> 34:02.000
in whatever sense is, in theory, represented within the price?

34:02.000 --> 34:07.000
That if there is, in theory, 10 euros of value within this item,

34:07.000 --> 34:10.000
that the price of this will be 10 euros,

34:10.000 --> 34:13.000
and that the capacity for calculation,

34:13.000 --> 34:17.000
the markets to calculate this or central computer to calculate this,

34:17.000 --> 34:20.000
that there is some either correspondence

34:20.000 --> 34:22.000
between the price and the underlying value

34:22.000 --> 34:24.000
or distortion of correspondence

34:24.000 --> 34:27.000
between the price and the underlying value.

34:27.000 --> 34:31.000
And so for Hayek, the socialist pricing problem

34:31.000 --> 34:34.000
represented a distortion of value

34:34.000 --> 34:37.000
in that it could never really know

34:37.000 --> 34:39.000
whether something was overpriced or underpriced

34:39.000 --> 34:42.000
because it couldn't calculate it fast enough.

34:42.000 --> 34:45.000
What many of those, it's not my idea,

34:45.000 --> 34:47.000
but many of those working in fields of ecological economics

34:47.000 --> 34:51.000
have identified is that there's a different kind of distortion

34:51.000 --> 34:54.000
that's happening within the market price

34:54.000 --> 35:02.000
in that there are underlying social and ecological costs

35:02.000 --> 35:07.000
to the production and transaction and consumption of commodities

35:07.000 --> 35:10.000
that are not reflected in the price.

35:10.000 --> 35:12.000
These are called negative externalities.

35:12.000 --> 35:16.000
They would include, so if that $100 barrel of oil,

35:16.000 --> 35:21.000
if it costs $100 because the amount that's available

35:21.000 --> 35:24.000
on the world market at any point in time

35:24.000 --> 35:29.000
would suggest that this is the price of it,

35:29.000 --> 35:33.000
what that price signal does not include, for example,

35:33.000 --> 35:38.000
are the immediate and or long-term costs of burning that oil,

35:38.000 --> 35:43.000
of releasing that, of liberating that carbon into the atmosphere,

35:43.000 --> 35:47.000
and the costs of its ramifications,

35:47.000 --> 35:50.000
whether those are immediate health costs

35:50.000 --> 35:53.000
or long-term subtraction costs.

35:53.000 --> 35:56.000
We were having a lot of discussions with colleagues

35:56.000 --> 35:59.000
around negative emissions technologies

35:59.000 --> 36:04.000
and the need for not only the decarbonization,

36:04.000 --> 36:07.000
not putting more carbon into the atmosphere,

36:07.000 --> 36:10.000
but the subtraction of existing carbon from the atmosphere

36:10.000 --> 36:13.000
in order to keep it 2 degrees Celsius.

36:13.000 --> 36:15.000
The real question of this is how do you pay for it?

36:15.000 --> 36:17.000
Well, part of the reason you can't pay for it

36:17.000 --> 36:20.000
is because the cost of the production of that carbon

36:20.000 --> 36:23.000
in the first place was not reflected

36:23.000 --> 36:28.000
in the price signal of the oil that produced that carbon

36:28.000 --> 36:31.000
in its first instance, as you see.

36:31.000 --> 36:35.000
And so this represents a distortion of the pricing.

36:35.000 --> 36:37.000
The question then for going to this question

36:37.000 --> 36:40.000
of what planetary scale computation is for

36:40.000 --> 36:42.000
is to ask the question is,

36:42.000 --> 36:45.000
would it be possible to undistort this signal?

36:45.000 --> 36:50.000
Would it be possible for there to be a price signal

36:50.000 --> 36:54.000
that was in essence not distorted in this way?

36:54.000 --> 36:57.000
It would have to be a price signal where, for example,

36:57.000 --> 37:01.000
the price of that barrel of oil would somehow be able to count,

37:01.000 --> 37:05.000
be inclusive of not just the transactional value,

37:05.000 --> 37:09.000
but ultimately all of the secondary and tertiary costs

37:09.000 --> 37:15.000
and value that would be associated with that item,

37:15.000 --> 37:18.000
such that it would be the cost of the barrel of mine

37:18.000 --> 37:21.000
being $500 a barrel or $1,500 a barrel,

37:21.000 --> 37:25.000
if that's what it would cost to actually deal with this.

37:25.000 --> 37:28.000
Now, what I sort of hypothesize in the book a bit

37:28.000 --> 37:30.000
more of as a thought experiment

37:30.000 --> 37:33.000
than as a policy recommendation

37:33.000 --> 37:36.000
is to ask them what you would need then is some ability

37:36.000 --> 37:43.000
for some kind of economics calculative substrate

37:43.000 --> 37:45.000
that was able not just to identify

37:45.000 --> 37:47.000
the immediate transactional relations,

37:47.000 --> 37:53.000
but to hypothesize a futural value of that,

37:53.000 --> 37:57.000
to imagine in the future what the cost of that would be

37:57.000 --> 37:59.000
that has not happened yet.

37:59.000 --> 38:01.000
So you burn the barrel of oil in the future

38:01.000 --> 38:03.000
that will be these costs that are associated with it

38:03.000 --> 38:05.000
in the form of negative externalities,

38:05.000 --> 38:08.000
but how much is that for one barrel of oil

38:08.000 --> 38:10.000
or for 10 barrels of oil or for one bicycle

38:10.000 --> 38:13.000
or for one lunch or for one whatever?

38:13.000 --> 38:16.000
There would be a future cost that hasn't happened yet.

38:16.000 --> 38:19.000
There would have to be a way, in essence, to price the future.

38:19.000 --> 38:22.000
How would you calculate the pricing of the future

38:22.000 --> 38:26.000
into the transaction in some kind of way?

38:26.000 --> 38:29.000
So this sort of led us to some of the questions

38:29.000 --> 38:32.000
about the ways in which planetary scale computation

38:32.000 --> 38:37.000
has already been used as a method for futural modeling

38:37.000 --> 38:40.000
and the production of models of the future

38:40.000 --> 38:43.000
that can or should have some recursive capacity

38:43.000 --> 38:45.000
to govern the present.

38:45.000 --> 38:47.000
And that's really what I think this question

38:47.000 --> 38:49.000
of the capitalist pricing,

38:49.000 --> 38:52.000
the de-distortion of the capitalist pricing

38:52.000 --> 38:54.000
that it comes down to,

38:54.000 --> 38:58.000
how can objective empirical statistically valid models

38:58.000 --> 39:01.000
of the future govern the present in some kind of way?

39:02.000 --> 39:05.000
So that includes, there's a lot of other discussions

39:05.000 --> 39:08.000
about just the general capacities of prospection,

39:08.000 --> 39:13.000
of how it is that the predictive structures of the future

39:14.000 --> 39:16.000
as part of human cognition play into this,

39:16.000 --> 39:19.000
the ways in which the kind of preemptive logics

39:19.000 --> 39:22.000
of the biopolitics of planetary scale computation

39:22.000 --> 39:23.000
play into this.

39:23.000 --> 39:26.000
But we were looking at basically two things.

39:26.000 --> 39:29.000
One was climate science.

39:29.000 --> 39:32.000
And one of the, I think the key points for this

39:32.000 --> 39:36.000
is that I make the argument that climate change itself,

39:36.000 --> 39:39.000
not the physical geophysical fact of climate change,

39:39.000 --> 39:42.000
but the concept of climate change,

39:42.000 --> 39:44.000
the statistical regularity that the earth is warming,

39:44.000 --> 39:47.000
is itself an epistemological accomplishment

39:47.000 --> 39:49.000
of planetary scale computation.

39:49.000 --> 39:52.000
That without this sensing, calculation, simulation,

39:52.000 --> 39:55.000
modeling apparatus of planetary scale computation,

39:55.000 --> 39:59.000
the very idea of climate change as a kind of

39:59.000 --> 40:04.000
reductive statistical regularity of a hockey stick arc

40:04.000 --> 40:06.000
of all of the things that are going on in the planet

40:06.000 --> 40:07.000
could not be possible.

40:07.000 --> 40:10.000
And one of the things, it wasn't possible to calculate.

40:10.000 --> 40:13.000
This is a better example of what planetary scale computation

40:13.000 --> 40:18.000
is for, if you ask me, and a different kind of model

40:18.000 --> 40:20.000
of its ultimate social, technical,

40:20.000 --> 40:22.000
and ecological potential.

40:22.000 --> 40:24.000
But it's also one that is based on this,

40:24.000 --> 40:28.000
of a kind of a temporal and historical differential

40:28.000 --> 40:30.000
between the past and the future.

40:30.000 --> 40:33.000
It's used not only to mark a present moment,

40:33.000 --> 40:36.000
but also to sample moments in the past

40:36.000 --> 40:39.000
through ice core sampling or other kinds of things

40:39.000 --> 40:43.000
to try to understand the kind of the calculus,

40:43.000 --> 40:45.000
the statistical differential arc of this

40:45.000 --> 40:47.000
over a long period of time,

40:47.000 --> 40:49.000
and also to produce valid computational simulations

40:50.000 --> 40:52.000
of what the next 10 years, or 20 years,

40:52.000 --> 40:54.000
or 30 years, or 40 years are being like.

40:54.000 --> 40:56.000
And so when we look at all the IPCC scenarios,

40:56.000 --> 40:58.000
and they're forking into the future,

40:58.000 --> 41:00.000
depending on what happens,

41:00.000 --> 41:02.000
these are computational simulations

41:02.000 --> 41:07.000
dependent upon different presumptions and first principles.

41:07.000 --> 41:11.000
But they are models of the future that we can

41:11.000 --> 41:14.000
and should be using to govern the present.

41:14.000 --> 41:17.000
That's what climate science is going to do for it.

41:17.000 --> 41:19.000
And so this is one example by which, yes,

41:19.000 --> 41:22.000
we can imagine ways in which we have models of the future

41:22.000 --> 41:25.000
that we wish to have recursively come back

41:25.000 --> 41:27.000
and model the present.

41:27.000 --> 41:30.000
The other one, a bit more prosaic that we've been

41:30.000 --> 41:34.000
experimenting with is around, of all things, insurance.

41:34.000 --> 41:40.000
Insurance is another way in which the future is priced,

41:40.000 --> 41:45.000
and that it's priced in a way that acts back upon

41:45.000 --> 41:49.000
the changes, the price signal of something we do in the present.

41:49.000 --> 41:55.000
So if you're, one of my favorite magazines of all time

41:55.000 --> 41:58.000
is a magazine called Schaden Spiegel.

41:58.000 --> 42:02.000
It's the magazine of the German Reinsurance Agency.

42:02.000 --> 42:05.000
It's basically like disaster monthly,

42:05.000 --> 42:11.000
but it also has some of the most amazingly sober

42:11.000 --> 42:15.000
descriptions of the implications of climate change

42:15.000 --> 42:18.000
on large-scale infrastructure that you'll be able to find anywhere.

42:18.000 --> 42:21.000
Because they're the ones on the hook for a lot of this,

42:21.000 --> 42:24.000
ultimately, of where this would go.

42:24.000 --> 42:27.000
And so if you wanted to build that piece of infrastructure,

42:27.000 --> 42:29.000
not only does it need to be insured,

42:29.000 --> 42:31.000
but the insurance company needs to get reinsurance against it.

42:31.000 --> 42:34.000
And if the reinsurance company realizes that that thing

42:34.000 --> 42:37.000
is going to be extremely vulnerable to climate irregularities,

42:37.000 --> 42:40.000
you can't get it insured.

42:40.000 --> 42:43.000
Or if you get it insured, the price of doing it now

42:43.000 --> 42:46.000
is going to be so much higher because that insurance policy

42:46.000 --> 42:49.000
will be so expensive that it actually changes the price signal

42:49.000 --> 42:53.000
of whether we should build that infrastructure thing in the first place.

42:53.000 --> 42:55.000
So you see where I'm going with this.

42:55.000 --> 43:00.000
That if you can actually think about what the long-term climatic ramifications

43:00.000 --> 43:04.000
of some kind of action or investment would be in the future,

43:04.000 --> 43:09.000
such that those negative externalities are not only not excluded

43:09.000 --> 43:14.000
from the price, but are formed the basis of the model

43:14.000 --> 43:18.000
by which the price is produced in the first place.

43:18.000 --> 43:24.000
Then you go some distance towards at least de-distorting

43:24.000 --> 43:30.000
that initial price signal in such a way that you have a transformation

43:30.000 --> 43:35.000
to some extent what we even mean by price in the first place.

43:35.000 --> 43:40.000
You introduce a different temporality to economic ontology,

43:40.000 --> 43:46.000
and that what constitutes value is being produced

43:46.000 --> 43:52.000
in relationship to not only future value in the same way

43:52.000 --> 43:55.000
as stock price is related to future value,

43:55.000 --> 44:00.000
but also related to future costs in ways in which that are inclusive in this.

44:00.000 --> 44:05.000
This is a bit what we mean by that idea.

44:05.000 --> 44:10.000
Obviously, some of the open questions here is how total of a system

44:10.000 --> 44:13.000
is necessary for this to work.

44:13.000 --> 44:18.000
Is there a way in which does this have to be entirely some sort

44:18.000 --> 44:22.000
of massively centralized mechanism, but through which other forms

44:22.000 --> 44:27.000
of valuation can't escape, or is there some kind of way

44:27.000 --> 44:32.000
in which even the organized participation

44:32.000 --> 44:40.000
within a kind of economics of this sort that is futureal in this way,

44:40.000 --> 44:47.000
that is inclusive of what are present externalities in some sort of way,

44:47.000 --> 44:53.000
is there some kind of way that participation on this can be incentivized

44:53.000 --> 45:00.000
in a way in which it itself becomes a kind of catalytic institution,

45:00.000 --> 45:04.000
a kind of bottom-up institution rather than necessarily one

45:04.000 --> 45:11.000
that requires some kind of Skynet system to enforce itself.

45:11.000 --> 45:15.000
I think that's kind of an open question,

45:15.000 --> 45:19.000
which means that in a certain way we're back to where we started.

45:20.000 --> 45:24.000
Is that if all of this started in a debate between is it possible to have,

45:24.000 --> 45:28.000
can we only have bottom-up organization of this and will it work itself out,

45:28.000 --> 45:31.000
or do we need some kind of centralized top-down piloting function

45:31.000 --> 45:33.000
to make all of this work properly?

45:33.000 --> 45:37.000
If that's where this argument started in the 1950s,

45:37.000 --> 45:40.000
even when we're talking about how you incentivize participation

45:40.000 --> 45:44.000
within this situation I described,

45:44.000 --> 45:49.000
that question doesn't present itself as already solved.

45:51.000 --> 45:56.000
This is super interesting and I think there's a different layer to it,

45:56.000 --> 45:59.000
which is quite important as well,

45:59.000 --> 46:02.000
because actually I think what you're kind of saying is that

46:02.000 --> 46:07.000
the future is already priced, but it could be priced much better.

46:07.000 --> 46:11.000
And this kind of stays within the realm of pricing the future

46:11.000 --> 46:17.000
and argues for better models and the incorporation of externalities

46:17.000 --> 46:20.000
specifically into the question of pricing.

46:20.000 --> 46:22.000
For example, yes.

46:22.000 --> 46:25.000
But there is a different level,

46:25.000 --> 46:29.000
and maybe this is the homo sapiens level at the end,

46:29.000 --> 46:31.000
there's a different level to this.

46:31.000 --> 46:34.000
And Evgeny Morozov writes about it in his essay

46:34.000 --> 46:37.000
in the New Left Review on Digital Socialism,

46:37.000 --> 46:39.000
and I'd like to quote him here,

46:39.000 --> 46:43.000
When Austrian economists respond to today's defenders of central planning

46:43.000 --> 46:46.000
by noting that any non-capitalist system,

46:46.000 --> 46:49.000
even one rooted in the power of big data,

46:49.000 --> 46:52.000
could only beat the efficiency of the price system

46:52.000 --> 46:57.000
if it also created new behavioral modes and frameworks of meaning,

46:57.000 --> 46:59.000
they have a point.

46:59.000 --> 47:01.000
I think this is super important

47:01.000 --> 47:04.000
and I think it's relevant for what you just said as well,

47:04.000 --> 47:07.000
and at least in two key aspects,

47:07.000 --> 47:12.000
it's relevant for the question of synthetic catalectsies to come,

47:12.000 --> 47:16.000
specifically if they are embedded in some form of red futurism.

47:16.000 --> 47:19.000
The first one would be, and this is implicit in Morozov's quote,

47:19.000 --> 47:22.000
that prices are not just numerical, but social,

47:22.000 --> 47:25.000
and that it is therefore not enough to find a different method

47:25.000 --> 47:27.000
of quantification or weighing.

47:27.000 --> 47:30.000
So this would kind of mean that it's not enough

47:30.000 --> 47:33.000
to price the future even better,

47:33.000 --> 47:36.000
because there's still the question of new behavioral modes

47:36.000 --> 47:38.000
and frameworks of meaning,

47:38.000 --> 47:41.000
which are kind of an obstacle and a chance, I guess.

47:41.000 --> 47:45.000
And the second one is that markets are not equal to capital

47:45.000 --> 47:49.000
and that capital does not necessarily need markets,

47:49.000 --> 47:52.000
and that therefore the force of capital as such

47:52.000 --> 47:55.000
would need to be abolished if one wanted to be serious

47:55.000 --> 47:58.000
about synthetic catalectsies as red futurism.

47:58.000 --> 48:01.000
And this is a specific form, you know?

48:01.000 --> 48:04.000
So I think those are probably two questions,

48:04.000 --> 48:07.000
and maybe if I just, so I can keep them in my mind at once,

48:07.000 --> 48:10.000
maybe we ask them, I'll try to answer them one at a time,

48:10.000 --> 48:13.000
and maybe you can ask me the second one again after this as well.

48:13.000 --> 48:18.000
So I would say that I don't disagree,

48:18.000 --> 48:22.000
I probably don't disagree essentially with the point that

48:23.000 --> 48:26.000
that simply another,

48:26.000 --> 48:29.000
just a different means of calculating price

48:29.000 --> 48:32.000
about the same thing would be sufficient.

48:32.000 --> 48:36.000
What I'm calling a kind of a shift in economic ontology

48:36.000 --> 48:39.000
goes to that question of what value is

48:39.000 --> 48:42.000
and what is even being priced in the first place.

48:42.000 --> 48:45.000
So it's not just when we're talking about a barrel of oil,

48:45.000 --> 48:49.000
it's not just this particular assemblage of molecules

48:49.000 --> 48:51.000
that is transacting owners,

48:51.000 --> 48:55.000
but it's understood to be a whole other set

48:55.000 --> 48:58.000
of past, present, and future dynamics

48:58.000 --> 49:03.000
that one has illegal liability in its relationship to

49:03.000 --> 49:05.000
that becomes part of the price.

49:05.000 --> 49:08.000
And I think another way in which this goes back to this question

49:08.000 --> 49:10.000
of insurance and another future thing,

49:10.000 --> 49:15.000
part of the question about price has to do with,

49:15.000 --> 49:18.000
and another kind of externality is a political externality

49:18.000 --> 49:22.000
in that it is the institutions that allow in essence

49:22.000 --> 49:26.000
for the renunciation of liability in relationship to something.

49:26.000 --> 49:29.000
And you can just think, I mean, in the simplest possible sense,

49:29.000 --> 49:32.000
think of this in terms of like trash.

49:32.000 --> 49:34.000
So like you've got something in your house

49:34.000 --> 49:37.000
and you put it out in the garbage can

49:37.000 --> 49:39.000
and like someone comes along and takes it and says,

49:39.000 --> 49:41.000
well, this isn't yours anymore

49:41.000 --> 49:43.000
because you put it in the trash, right?

49:43.000 --> 49:46.000
And somehow in the act of like getting rid of it,

49:46.000 --> 49:50.000
you're not only renouncing property claims over it,

49:50.000 --> 49:55.000
you're also renouncing liability claims over it as well, right?

49:55.000 --> 49:58.000
And so part of the process of the reason

49:58.000 --> 50:01.000
why negative externalities can even work in this way

50:01.000 --> 50:06.000
is because we have this magic function

50:06.000 --> 50:09.000
by which the renunciation of private property

50:09.000 --> 50:12.000
constitutes the renunciation of liability.

50:13.000 --> 50:16.000
So I can spew all of the carbon dioxide

50:16.000 --> 50:19.000
into the atmosphere once I want.

50:19.000 --> 50:24.000
And once it's sort of above the airspace property line

50:25.000 --> 50:28.000
of my factory, it's no longer my carbon dioxide,

50:28.000 --> 50:31.000
and therefore I'm no longer liable for this carbon dioxide.

50:31.000 --> 50:35.000
So you see the point about this renunciation of liability

50:35.000 --> 50:36.000
in this space as well.

50:36.000 --> 50:39.000
Now, what I'm talking about as the shift

50:39.000 --> 50:44.000
of a kind of economic ontology has to do some ways

50:44.000 --> 50:48.000
in which that magic function of renunciation of liability

50:48.000 --> 50:52.000
and renunciation of sort of embeddedness

50:52.000 --> 50:55.000
within these socio-molecular relations

50:56.000 --> 50:59.000
is not something that can be so easily renounced,

50:59.000 --> 51:01.000
that is in fact part of what you're buying

51:01.000 --> 51:03.000
when you enter into the relations

51:03.000 --> 51:06.000
with that barrel of oil in the first place.

51:06.000 --> 51:09.000
So that is part of what I mean.

51:09.000 --> 51:11.000
So that is a bit where it seems like

51:11.000 --> 51:14.000
I probably agree with Evgeny in the sense to which

51:14.000 --> 51:16.000
it's not just a matter of finding another mechanism

51:16.000 --> 51:18.000
by which we measure the same thing.

51:18.000 --> 51:20.000
It's a matter of changing

51:20.000 --> 51:22.000
what we're measuring in the first place.

51:23.000 --> 51:25.000
But where I would say, where it may be disagree,

51:25.000 --> 51:26.000
when he says something like,

51:26.000 --> 51:27.000
I think your line was a measure,

51:27.000 --> 51:30.000
it's not just a matter of measuring and calculating

51:30.000 --> 51:33.000
something but rather something else

51:33.000 --> 51:34.000
because these have social relations.

51:34.000 --> 51:36.000
I think my point is that measuring and calculating

51:36.000 --> 51:37.000
are social relations.

51:40.000 --> 51:42.000
What he's saying is it can't just be

51:42.000 --> 51:44.000
these measuring things because it's social.

51:44.000 --> 51:46.000
I'm saying that is in fact what the social is.

51:46.000 --> 51:49.000
Measuring things and calculating things and weighing things

51:49.000 --> 51:51.000
not only have social functions,

51:51.000 --> 51:53.000
they are social functions.

51:53.000 --> 51:56.000
They are sort of the key social functions

51:56.000 --> 52:01.000
as part of this whole kind of dynamic as well.

52:01.000 --> 52:05.000
And so it is for sure something that needs to go deeper

52:05.000 --> 52:07.000
into this question of how we identify

52:07.000 --> 52:09.000
not only how we value the thing

52:09.000 --> 52:11.000
but what the thing is in the first place.

52:11.000 --> 52:12.000
So agreed.

52:12.000 --> 52:14.000
Now whether or not this constitutes

52:14.000 --> 52:18.000
a kind of behavioral change, it would.

52:18.000 --> 52:21.000
It's a matter of, it's an open question though

52:21.000 --> 52:23.000
I think whether or not the behavioral

52:23.000 --> 52:25.000
and psychological transformation would be the cause

52:25.000 --> 52:26.000
or the effect.

52:28.000 --> 52:30.000
And honestly there's sort of different approaches

52:30.000 --> 52:33.000
and schools of thought to this.

52:33.000 --> 52:36.000
And this probably goes to a more deeper

52:36.000 --> 52:39.000
sort of approaches to ecological politics

52:39.000 --> 52:43.000
and indeed just the kind of dynamics in general.

52:43.000 --> 52:45.000
For those whose alliance,

52:45.000 --> 52:47.000
whose those sort of like way of seeing the world

52:47.000 --> 52:51.000
is one in which large scale change happens

52:51.000 --> 52:54.000
through the accumulation of virtuous acts.

52:54.000 --> 52:58.000
That if enough people do enough virtuous acts

52:59.000 --> 53:02.000
and those virtuous acts assemble into millions and billions

53:02.000 --> 53:04.000
and trillions of virtuous acts,

53:04.000 --> 53:07.000
then there will be an infrastructural transformation

53:07.000 --> 53:12.000
will ensue through this deliberate conscious

53:14.000 --> 53:19.000
psychological moral shift in paradigmatic worldview

53:21.000 --> 53:25.000
and then the accumulation of virtuous acts.

53:25.000 --> 53:26.000
And then there's others.

53:26.000 --> 53:29.000
And I would be on the second side of this a bit more

53:29.000 --> 53:32.000
that would suggest in many ways the history of technology

53:32.000 --> 53:34.000
and the history of society are not only intertwined

53:34.000 --> 53:37.000
with one another, but in many respects,

53:37.000 --> 53:40.000
shifts in social systems and in cultural systems

53:40.000 --> 53:42.000
and indeed in political and economic systems

53:42.000 --> 53:47.000
usually happen more as an effect of transformations

53:47.000 --> 53:51.000
within underlying technological systems.

53:51.000 --> 53:53.000
This is in a certain sense

53:53.000 --> 53:56.000
based a superstructure kind of approach

53:56.000 --> 53:59.000
that in transformations not just in the means of production,

53:59.000 --> 54:01.000
but indeed in the mode of production

54:02.000 --> 54:05.000
that you then see shifts in culture

54:05.000 --> 54:08.000
and shifts in psychology as a result of these.

54:08.000 --> 54:10.000
And so I think in many respects,

54:10.000 --> 54:15.000
my inclination would be to look at ways

54:15.000 --> 54:19.000
in which you'll get greater leverage faster

54:19.000 --> 54:24.000
by looking at ways in which there would be shifts

54:24.000 --> 54:27.000
in geotechnology and shifts in geoeconomics

54:27.000 --> 54:30.000
that would bring about shifts in geoculture

54:30.000 --> 54:35.000
rather than trying to bring about a spiritual transformation

54:36.000 --> 54:40.000
that would subsequently down the line

54:40.000 --> 54:42.000
transform those geotechnologies.

54:42.000 --> 54:45.000
It's really not because of an aesthetic preference

54:45.000 --> 54:47.000
of this so much, but rather than just,

54:47.000 --> 54:49.000
I think that the history of economics

54:49.000 --> 54:51.000
and the history of technology suggest

54:51.000 --> 54:55.000
that that's the more likely path.

54:56.000 --> 54:59.000
But at least as far as I understand it,

54:59.000 --> 55:01.000
the question that he's aiming at when he's saying

55:01.000 --> 55:04.000
new behavioral modes and frameworks of meaning,

55:04.000 --> 55:08.000
it's more about what are the crucial points

55:08.000 --> 55:13.000
that are not only concerned with these technical aspects

55:13.000 --> 55:17.000
of, for example, how to price the future any better

55:17.000 --> 55:20.000
because these ideas of externalities

55:20.000 --> 55:24.000
and how you can behave with your property,

55:24.000 --> 55:28.000
this is ingrained in the very concept of property as such.

55:28.000 --> 55:32.000
So if you are not able to change this idea of property

55:32.000 --> 55:36.000
as a form of behavioral mode and a framework of meaning,

55:36.000 --> 55:41.000
then you won't get to a point where you will be effective

55:41.000 --> 55:46.000
in bringing people to a point of not treating it

55:47.000 --> 55:49.000
as an externality.

55:49.000 --> 55:50.000
Do you see what I mean?

55:50.000 --> 55:53.000
I think there's a way of approaching it

55:53.000 --> 55:55.000
from the perspective of, okay, we need to find

55:55.000 --> 55:59.000
a more effective pricing mechanism for these externalities,

55:59.000 --> 56:03.000
or we need to find a way to address this social institution

56:03.000 --> 56:06.000
of property as such because the property as such,

56:06.000 --> 56:09.000
as a social institution and a framework of meaning,

56:09.000 --> 56:12.000
is one of the root causes for the ways we do address

56:12.000 --> 56:15.000
these questions on a large scale.

56:15.000 --> 56:18.000
And this is not coming from a moral perspective,

56:18.000 --> 56:22.000
but as well from a perspective of effectiveness, I guess.

56:22.000 --> 56:24.000
Possibly.

56:24.000 --> 56:26.000
I agree with you everything up to the point of the phrase

56:26.000 --> 56:27.000
root cause.

56:27.000 --> 56:30.000
I see it as root effect.

56:30.000 --> 56:36.000
I completely agree with you that ultimately you can't have

56:36.000 --> 56:38.000
one without the other.

56:38.000 --> 56:40.000
I don't argue with this at all.

56:44.000 --> 56:48.000
If there is a changing in somehow, even at the level

56:48.000 --> 56:51.000
of some shift in the geotechnology of pricing

56:51.000 --> 56:54.000
and organization and the ontology of property

56:54.000 --> 56:58.000
that has some kind of planetary scale legal binding structure,

56:58.000 --> 57:05.000
if this isn't, in fact, become part of the culture

57:05.000 --> 57:08.000
of our relationship to object and molecular assemblages

57:08.000 --> 57:10.000
around us and our socioeconomic environment,

57:10.000 --> 57:13.000
if it doesn't actually become a social infrastructure

57:13.000 --> 57:18.000
and doesn't actually become the basis of the way

57:18.000 --> 57:22.000
in which we plan, conceptualize, model,

57:22.000 --> 57:26.000
and recursively organize our relationship

57:26.000 --> 57:29.000
to the material world, then it's nothing.

57:29.000 --> 57:34.000
It's not even a technology because it's not being used.

57:34.000 --> 57:35.000
There's no argument.

57:35.000 --> 57:37.000
I absolutely agree.

57:37.000 --> 57:39.000
And then part of the question is, how is it

57:39.000 --> 57:44.000
that at societal levels that the kind of models

57:44.000 --> 57:50.000
that we have, cognitive models, at an individual level

57:50.000 --> 57:53.000
and at a group level, cognitive models that understand

57:53.000 --> 57:58.000
and calculate advantage, calculate the future,

57:58.000 --> 58:01.000
calculate our interests, calculate our interactions

58:02.000 --> 58:06.000
with these kinds of things are done so in relationship

58:06.000 --> 58:08.000
to these differential systems.

